1","–Female":"Deceased","about 1149":"about 1149","1221":"1221","1120":"1120","1150":"1150","1194":"1194","Between 1150 and 1160":"from 1150 to 1160","Arkesden, Essex, England":"Arkesden, Essex, England","Willingale Doe at Arkenden, Saffron Walden, Essex, England":"Saffron Walden, Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rockhill","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Middlesex and Surrey): perhaps a habitational name from any of several minor places called Rockhill, such as Rockhill Farm in Stourton Caundle (Dorset) or Rockhill Farm in Greete (Shropshire). However, early forms for these particular places have not been found and so the surname may alternatively be a variant of   Rochelle   (compare   Rockett  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rochelle","meanings":["French (mainly Ille-et-Vilaine) and English (Staffordshire; of Norman origin): habitational name from (La) Rochelle, the name of several places in various parts of France, especially that in Manche, from a diminutive of Old French <i>roche</i> ‘rock, cliff, promontory’. In Britain, the surname is often recorded in its Norman French form <i>Rokel(l)e</i>.","French (Alsace): variant of   Rochel  ."]}]},{"name":"Mrs","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from Latin <i>Ursus</i> ‘bear’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Richard Rockhill married Richard De La Rokele I about 1149, in Arkesden, Essex, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1120–1194":"1120–1194","1150–1221":"1150–1221","–Female":"Surnud","about 1149":"umbes 1149","1221":"1221","1120":"1120","1150":"1150","1194":"1194","Between 1150 and 1160":"1150 kuni 1160","Arkesden, Essex, England":"Arkesden, Essex, England","Willingale Doe at Arkenden, Saffron Walden, Essex, England":"Saffron Walden, Essex, England"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1120–1194":"1120–1194","1150–1221":"1150–1221","–Female":"Kuollut","about 1149":"noin 1149","1221":"1221","1120":"1120","1150":"1150","1194":"1194","Between 1150 and 1160":"vuodesta 1150 vuoteen 1160","Arkesden, Essex, England":"Arkesden, Essex, England","Willingale Doe at Arkenden, Saffron Walden, Essex, England":"Saffron Walden, Essex, England"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","1120–1194":"1120–1194","1150–1221":"1150–1221","–Female":"Décédée","about 1149":"environ 1149","1221":"1221","1120":"1120"